Higgs boson explored
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson caused a legitimate stir last summer.
There is an opinion that this boson is involved in a mechanism that is responsible for all the matter in the universe.
And it's also the last particle that the standard model predicts exists -- our best or least bad explanation of the nature and behavior of matter -- but it hasn't been empirically observed yet.
But physicists are still not 100% sure that it's a Higgs boson.
There's no doubt that we have a completely new particle that looks very much like the Higgs boson, as predicted by the standard model.
The new data released this week at the great Physics Congress in Kyoto confirms this, but we still lack all the data to be absolutely certain.
However, let's assume it's the Higgs boson, because the risk of error seems small, and let's see what it actually is.
In this world, there is a perfectly unquestionable law that says that two things cannot happen at the same time in the same place.
This rule cannot be circumvented - and do not try too hard or you will hurt yourself.
Although particle physics is a very strange world, it does show a similar law: Pauli's exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - that "state" creates some of their properties, in a nutshell.
Then he divides the physical particles into two categories.
On the one hand, we find orderly citizens, or fermions, who obey the Pauli principle.
And at the other end are bosons, vicious anarchists who don't care about anything at all -- certainly not this principle, which means they can be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are further divided into two groups by device (except for the amazing one) which is The Particle Adventure at Berkeley Labs: mesons, which we leave unnoticed here, and "force particles", which are spread by great natural forces and with which the Higgs boson is probably somehow related.
However, it must be said that these bosons are not as exotic animals as one might think.
If you are reading this article, it is because of an unusual banality of the boson: a photon, or "particle of light", that is the "carrier" of electromagnetic force.
When an electrically charged particle accelerates or changes direction, it "disrupts" the electromagnetic field at that particular location, much like a spark thrown into a pond.
This "disturbance" produces an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.) and this wave is nothing more than a photon - and thus one of the bosons, the "force carriers".
More stable field
It's the same with the Higgs boson, except that it needs to be disturbed by another field, the Higgs field, to make this boson appear.
This Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, you have to achieve very high energy values, much like the frozen lake level, which is already lit by a very large balvan.
For this reason, it is necessary to use a part accelerator as massive as the accelerator in CERN -- a large hadron accelerator with a circular loop of 27 km! -- to produce such energy.
An analogy with the electromagnetic field is again useful to clarify the relationship between Higgs and matter.
Because not all particles or materials react with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others do not - a piece of paper, for example, will never hold itself in the refrigerator.
And it's also true that not all particles react with the Higgs field: those that do have some matter, while the others (like the photon, let's look at it) don't.
And Mrs. Novak asks, what is all this research for, what will it bring us?
From a scientific point of view, this is a validation of the Standard Model (SM), which allows physicists to examine any inconsistency between the observation and prediction of SM.
And there are not many physicists who would literally wish that we could find them, because the slightest difference could open up the space of "new physics" and fill some gaps in the model.
It should be noted that the model still has huge flaws, it does not provide any clarification of gravity (oh!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the cosmic mass (oh again!).
CERN has not yet discovered such discrepancies.
Other
The impact of these studies on Mr and Mrs Novákov's daily life can only be predicted very difficultly, but it would be a mistake to assume that there would be none.
Look: even in the early 1960s, the pioneers of laser at Bell Labs had no idea of the revolution their work would bring.
They assumed scientific use, but nothing else.
Physicist Willard Boyle -- who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who created the first permanent laser beam (the previous beams were pulsed) in 1962, I've already said -- the laser was initially considered to be such a "laboratory toy".
Just imagine that...
And in addition, the application can also arise from all the instruments surrounding research.
For example, the same Willard Boyle created a small light sensor in 1969 during his work on optics.
This sensor, although Boyle initially did not plan it that way, now serves as the "eye" of all digital cameras in the world and earned him the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
Of course, that doesn't mean that the activities around the LHC necessarily have to change our lives, but it does mean that you really never know...
