There is no all-powerful care
Dr. Martel estimates that 90% of patients who wish to die thank their doctors for not fulfilling their wishes when the painkiller team relieved their pain.
But it must be said that palliative care is not necessarily omnipotent in treating pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at the Grand Montréal Home Palliative Care Society, 8% of patients are denied pain treatment.
At the very end of life, doctors often use a palliative sedative that will put the patient to sleep until the moment of death, whether by accident or by continuous sedation.
We can't pretend we don't see this part of suffering.
Patients who are not relieved of pain will have an increasingly high chance of receiving palliative sedatives.
Patients who are not given sedatives always say the same thing, "I want to die".
But it doesn't always mean "I want you to give me euthanasia", it means "I want you to take my pain away".
