In an interview with Microsoft's head of interactive 3D technology at Cambridge Labs, Sharam Izadim, it appears that for the company's scientists, glasses are a thing of the past.
The trick is the perspective of manipulating virtual objects in the air with bare hands, creating virtual public spaces.
- Can you tell us in a framework what your research team is doing?
- We're dealing with human-machine interactions, but at the same time we're trying to push the boundaries of that interaction.
So far, humanity has been stuck in the process of working with pixels on a flat screen, sometimes touching the screen with a finger.
We want to look five to 10 years ahead and predict significant changes in this interaction.
