- What do you think of voice control?
It's a popular thing, but isn't it overrated?
- Of course, he can't be considered a villain - the privacy issue arises because we don't always want to inform others in our community about our activities and intentions.
In fact, all types of computer interaction are good, but in their own environment.
For example, we had a project to control devices in public places where we thought about gestures, but not over-the-top, just the expensive, short ones.
The gesture would not be captured by a camera device, but by a bracelet that would monitor the movements of bones and muscles.
It's big, but theoretically it can be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But in general, the future has a mixed control type, like gesture + voice.
- How did you do that?
How do you ask me to give you this can of lemonade?
You say it and you show it at the same time.
- I usually just talk.
- Oh, that's going to be very hard to tell.
So you want to get users to adapt to what the machine can or can't do at the moment?
- It's not necessary, but it's a rapprochement.
I think in the near future we'll have to work primarily on developing new types of sensors that can more accurately detect human reactions.
These can be, for example, laser sensors that provide fairly good depth resolution, which is very important.
- Speaking of your work with Xbox Kinect sensors, what are your requirements for modern cameras?
Isn't there enough discernment, depth, or something else today?
- Basically, the current generation - that's what we can shake off in our work on 3D recognition.
Of course, it would be good to get 8 megapixels at 1,000 f/s.
But it's not just the megapixels themselves, but the matrix and the depth.
At the moment, all the current technology is not enough for us -- that adds to the work of algorithm designers.
So we have to keep in mind not only the resolution of the X and Y axes, but also the Z.
So what's really important is the speed, the number of images per second.
Human movement is quite dynamic, and the current data flows of 30 frames per second are, frankly, a little bit small, especially for gestures.
Stephen Betishes of our Redmond lab has made a touch sensor with a set processing delay of 1 to 100 ms, whereas the current, mass-produced sensors are closer to the second value (60-100 ms).
