Glasses -- this is a very personal device, and that's their strength (only you can see private things), and at the same time their weakness -- augmented reality based on glasses won't let you work on virtual objects at the same time as other people.
- Imagine for a moment that manipulation of virtual holographic objects in the air is available not only to Tony Stark in Iron Man, but to an ordinary mortal.
There is one problem that critics often point to: there is no tangible response!
My hands can't feel anything!
What are your group's responses to this challenge?
- In my lectures, I often say that augmented reality is the seventh successive breakthrough in human-machine interaction.
I think the addition of tangible perceptions could easily be the eighth breakthrough.
So far, one of the interesting tricks is using the second hand as a kind of visual substrate.
He's recording the pressure in a great way!
But there are also technologies that really aim to add tangibleness to these "air images" -- for example, interfering with several directional ultrasound beams at a defined point where the finger is located, it creates a tangible feeling, but it's still very weak -- like blowing your fingers in the belly.
There is also a wrist bracelet that affects the nerve endings in the fingers - also a promising direction.
- Have you tried to fool your brain?
To think he feels what he seems to feel at the moment when he sees something?
- That's a good idea. We haven't tried that yet.
Here's another challenge that will be fought for a long time - how to get a person who is physically in a very tight space to believe that he's walking through an open, virtually infinite space - we're also working on the concept of running tracks (not at all like clubs), moving platforms and also huge balls.
If brain-deception becomes a target, then work is still for many years.
That's what makes virtual reality work so appealing to researchers -- a lot of things are in the very beginning.
