Chief of the NCO: The control of the smuggling system failed because of politicians
The Czech Republic has good regulators and good quality legislation in the field of public procurement, but it is not very good at applying it.
In an interview with Aktuálně.cz, this is what the vice president of the Supreme Control Office, Miloslav Kala, says.
"The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct - that is what I think we lack", comments Kala on the current situation.
Similar conclusions are also suggested by a joint audit by the Czech and German auditors.
As an example of wrong practice, Peter Neczas cites the approach to the so-called "scamming system".
The Prime Minister recently said that the ODS will not bother the businessman with its controls - so is it prohibited or allowed?
"The law must be set up in some way, and if it prohibits something, then even the prime minister cannot prevent the work of the office that is obliged to check and enforce the duties", says Kala.
At the meeting of the House of Representatives' control committee, you spoke about a joint project between the Czech and German parties, in which the legislation on public procurement in both countries was compared.
What was it, exactly?
It's a parallel check we started about two years ago.
In simple terms, European legislation regulates the way in which public procurement is handled, followed by individual national legislation and then by practice itself.
We have put all this together, and although the audit is not yet complete, we have found very interesting differences - in general, the legislation is perhaps "more rigorous and more perfect" here, but the practice itself is in some respects better in Germany.
It is therefore clear that it is not enough to create ever more precise rules, but that the application of the law itself needs to be addressed.
What good can this project do for you, what good does it do for you?
It is this kind of joint control that could help us to stop making efforts to clarify laws, reduce and improve limits when it has no such positive impact.
Economics means acquiring a good at a reasonable (but not always the lowest) price to avoid enrichment and, if necessary, criminal conduct.
But by lowering the order limit, we don't necessarily have to achieve that.
Perhaps the system will be so overwhelmed with paper that those who want to look for holes in the system will find it much easier to draw on than if the limit remained higher.
You're talking about the domestic problems with the implementation of public procurement legislation.
How does the control system in Germany work?
Is there a similar office to our NKU, or is it set up differently?
As far as the authorities are concerned, the Bundesrechnungshof, which is organized like us, also has a college, but it is a little different, but basically both authorities operate in a similar way.
The powers are also somewhat similar, but since Germany has a federal system, it also has these courts at the level of individual federal countries - in this the system differs slightly from ours.
The BRH can only control federal money, represented here by state funds.
The public funds that are administered by our counties and municipalities are controlled at the federal level.
As far as the legislation there goes, is it simpler than ours?
In general, I would not like to compare this without specific data, however in some respects Germany is often referred to as a model, but it cannot be said with certainty that it is better at everything.
So, is it necessary that they have better controllers?
I'm sure not, but I'm saying again, I don't like that comparison.
But it has to be said that even the countries we consider to be the model face a number of problems.
Otherwise, there's no benefit to them from working with our office, right?
As for the domestic legislation, which meant for your office that the amendment to the Public Procurement Act was in effect, are its effects already being felt?
Since the validity period of this notice is relatively short, it has not yet been reflected in the control measures.
Since we're doing ex post checks, we need to expect some delay.
We are only seeing this so far in the process of preparing future checks - we have launched our new tool for "risk detection of insolvency", through which we have passed and analysed almost 14,000 public procurements - and those changes will of course be reflected there, because the limits will change, the conditions of some types of tender will be adjusted and so on.
So, do you consider the passage of this law a benefit or a further burden on the bureaucratic system?
I think this bill is definitely a step in the right direction, and I hope it's confirmed.
The problem here is that the rules will become "strict" and it won't be possible to follow them.
Already during the previous rules, the controlled persons are obliged by the provider (for example, in the case of regional operational programmes by the regional council) to consider that any non-compliance with the public procurement law constitutes a violation of the budgetary penalty.
Is it worth it to tighten the law in this way?
I don't think this way.
The system must exclude those who want to attack and exploit it, not punish those who make a formal mistake that has no impact on decision making.
Such a system will only put more pressure on the bureaucracy.
So how do you get out of it?
Let's see where the road leads.
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the SDGs would not bother businessmen with the controls of the so-called "switching system" - and what does that mean?
Is the punching system prohibited or allowed?
The law must be set up in some way, and if it prohibits something, the Prime Minister cannot prevent the work of an authority that is obliged to check and enforce its duties.
He can say, "We'll change the law and allow it", but he can't say we'll act like nothing.
The Public Procurement Act has quite strict rules on what is to be done formally - which is right to protect public competition.
