Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at a meeting of the European Space Agency's Ministers of State, Poland was admitted as the 20th member of the European Space Agency, the second country from the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on 12 November 2008).
Poland began working closely with ESA in 1994 and has been involved in a number of ESA projects over the years.
But Poland's journey into space began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts were already engaged in spaceflight before World War II; but they did not always meet with understanding.
For example, I recall A. Sternfeld's lecture at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory, which on December 6, 1933, presented ideas from his pioneering work Introduction to Cosmonautics.
The ideas of the young engineer (November 1905) left the audience cold, and after years, Šternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934 he was awarded the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize for his contribution to cosmonautics in France.
The noted Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899-1966) later became a great proponent of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish magazines and wrote a number of books devoted to these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski became a world-renowned promoter of cosmonautics, and his contribution was recognized by the fact that one of the craters on the far side of the Moon was named after him.
In 1925, a railway line was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of the proposal is unknown and the details of the project are not known.
It's also unclear whether the missile was intended to launch the tractor or to stop it.
Information about this drainage is known only from the periodical.
Since 1933, the Polish artillery has been surrounded by missiles.
The research was carried out by the Armed Forces Technical Unit in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolf and Prof. Gustav Mokrzyckieg.
It is clear from the preserved materials that the research has reached the stage of practical testing.
However, the arrival of German troops interrupted the research.
In 1937 a design of a photoelectric fighter missile was published in a professional press, designed by engineer Rohoziński, and the following year the work of the Raket - air torpedo and airship rocket bomb by Leliwy-Krzywoblockki was published.
Both projects were intended for military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) was devoted to all projects of military missile technology, which coordinated all the work.
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of activity, its activities ended with the start of the war.
Further works on cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Astronaut Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The first mention of the company was in the November 1954 issue of the journal Problemy, which included four more comprehensive articles on astronauts.
One of them, by Professor M. Subotowicz, proposes to create a society that deals with cosmonautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects were already underway, and it was clear that space exploration was a promising field.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) has been seeking membership in the International Astronautical Federation (founded 1951) and already in the autumn PTA became a full member.
And the following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902-1959) became the vice president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has been significantly involved in the development of the highly successful RM (Meteorological Rocket) which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first RM-1 was completed in 1957 and first launched on 10 October 1958.
The 1,800-meter-long missile was about 80 centimeters long and weighed less than 5 kilograms.
Later, an improved version of the RM-1A was built and in the summer of 1959 two-stage RM-2 missile flight tests were started in the Bledovsk Desert.
The missile was 1.4 meters long and weighed about 11.5 kilograms.
Another development type was already capable of real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket was to have a range of up to 14.5 km and its task was to track high winds.
However, in 1962 further development was halted.
The successor to the first RM-type rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket developed between 1962 and 1965.
The missile was designed as a two-stage, with a total length of 510 cm and a launch weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types (designated Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, varying in size from space to space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a capacity of 0.4 litres, the Meteor-1B 0.34 litres and the Meteor-1C 0.62 litres.
Maximum range for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Institute of Aviation, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had a launch weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg to an altitude of about 60 km.
Subsequently, versions of Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
It is also worth mentioning that Poland joined COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of the COSPAR National Committee two years later.
Poland also participated in the Interkosmos program in space research on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remk.
