Szabo: "Germans must play a bigger role"
Germany abstained from voting on the decision to accept Palestine.
According to US-European relations expert Stephen Szaboa, Berlin is thus on the brink of diplomacy.
Deutsche Welle: Germany first signaled earlier this week that it would vote against the proposal for Palestinian observer status in the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained from voting.
Why? Why?
Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis were doing in Gaza.
But now Germany must be cautious because of its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I don't think it's going to support the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - without being too critical of Israel.
In March 2011, Germany abstained from voting on the establishment of a no-fly zone.
NATO finally took over.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on major international issues?
Yes, it is.
The reason is that it is changing its foreign policy, from a policy that was so to speak US-led, to a German foreign policy.
The situation is made even more difficult by the lack of coherent and uniform policies among Europeans.
The Germans are between two fronts.
They're expected to play a more independent role, but they're not used to it.
I think they're just settling into their roles, but they're on their way to a more "normal" foreign policy.
To foreign policy, like they have in France or the UK.
What exactly does "normal" foreign policy mean from a German perspective?
It shows a willingness to take positions that are independent of the positions of the US or European partners in the case of national interests.
I think that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, that is, exports and its relations with certain areas, like Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests differ to some extent from those of other powers and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Did economic interests influence the Middle East stance and the UN vote?
First, Germany has a large supply chain in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf states.
So he must be careful not to scare the public, but also the elites in the Arab countries.
That's part of it anyway.
I don't want to give it too much weight, it's not a one-sided relationship.
However, it plays a significant role in the German considerations.
Did Germany's relations with the United States suffer when Germany abstained on both important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine?
I think there is a great deal of understanding in Europe and even in the United States of America for the German position.
That's why I don't think it was as dramatic a break as the Libyan issue.
I hope that Germany will even earn some respect.
This is a sign that he must be considered an international player and his interests must be taken into account.
There are different views in Europe on the Palestinian initiative.
The United States, on the other hand, has clearly vetoed the resolution.
Are there differences of opinion between the United States and many European nations?
These differences have always existed as a result of American domestic policy.
I think the Obama administration probably has a deep understanding of the European position.
But because of the political situation there, he cannot, of course, hold this position publicly.
I think the differences in opinion are not as great as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, Obama is not very enthusiastic about Netanyahu's politics at all.
Is it not difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States on the one hand and with the position of the most important partners in the EU on the other?
I think that's exactly what makes it harder for the Germans.
It would be a little easier for the Germans, of course, if there were a coherent and unified European policy, which is not happening at the moment.
So they can't be part of a wider line and they have to move things forward from their own position.
That's what they're doing with the euro.
I believe that Germany will take the lead in the future and push Europe towards a European position.
This is not easy for Germany, of course, given the relationship with Israel.
It's always been a sensitive subject.
But I think the Germans know they have to play a more independent role.
Does Germany see itself as a major international player?
Or is the leadership role still difficult for Germany?
Germany is still not used to it, it is still uncomfortable, and for obvious reasons it is still difficult for this country to play a bigger role.
If we look at the European crisis, for example, every time Germany takes a bigger role, anti-German sentiment arises.
It doesn't make it easy for the Germans.
It's actually an old problem: we don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
In this respect, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the United States.
It has to be acceptable to all kinds of neighbors and opinions, and it's not easy.
The US' influence in European politics is now declining, but the EU is not currently filling that vacuum.
The Germans will just have to play a bigger role.
Even if they don't like it, they're uncomfortable with it, and it makes them even more unpopular - c'est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is the Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., an institute where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America study together the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, U.S. foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
