The South American Summit is over and the Limassol Declaration is not published
The sixth presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) in Peru today ended without the release of the Declaration of Limits, which was announced and reportedly signed by the seven presidents present.
EFE has repeatedly tried to gain access to the document signed at the sixth Unasur Summit, but representatives of the Foreign Ministry and the Office of the President, who initially set out to publish the document after the summit, said it would be published later on the Peruvian government's website.
They also said that the content was published by Peruvian President Ollanta Humala in several brief press releases.
Journalists had limited access to information throughout the summit.
During the meeting, a video of the presidential meeting was broadcast in the press room with the message "Confidential meeting, No Sound Transmission".
The small amount of information that the journalists had was provided by press representatives of some governments who were present but not by Peruvian representatives.
The only document released during the meeting was a list of presidents attending, prompting hundreds of journalists from various national and international media to ask for more information.
The Peruvian presidential office later sent an e-mail with a "concluding statement" from the summit, but this is only a statement by President Humala, not an official document that concluded the summit.
Last October Peru hosted the third summit of South American and Arab countries (América del Sur-Países Árabes, ASPA) and even on this occasion the originally promised Declaration of Lima was not published, despite press press urges.
The official website of ASPA states that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, Peruvian authorities tried to ensure broadcasting for all journalists, but they completely prevented the transmission of information.
The Summit concluded, inter alia, with Chile and Peru's joint commitment to accept the judgment of the Hague Court of Justice, which resolves the border dispute between the two countries.
President Ollanta Humala of Peru and President Sebastián Piñera of Chile met during a regional meeting and confirmed that they would respect the ruling of the International Court of Justice in The Hague, which will begin hearing the defence of both parties on Monday to hear the dispute initiated by Lima against Santiago.
"We will proceed and execute a ruling that resolves the dispute we are hearing today in this international court", President Humala said along with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile was, is and will be a country that respects international law, peaceful dispute resolution, conventions and international courts", Piñera added, welcoming President Humalu with a handshake on the flags of both countries.
The confirmation by both presidents that they will submit to the decision of the International Court of Justice was made public after Colombia adopted the Bogotá Pact this week, expressing its submission to the judgments of the international court that ruled on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, and Colombia considered this decision to be completely wrong.
The summit was held without the participation of the Presidents of Brazil (Dilma Rouseff), Venezuela (Hugo Chavez), Bolivia (Evo Morales) and Argentina (Cristina Kirchner).
Paraguay was excluded from Unasur in 2011 following the removal of then President Fernando Luga and did not attend the meeting.
Host President Ollanta Humala was commissioned to begin the morning speeches and conclude the Lima Summit shortly after noon.
The President read the final document, which reported that 16 agreements had been signed and 31 projects were planned between South American countries, with an investment of $17 billion.
In addition to the agreements adopted, he noted that UNASUR member states would take "important steps towards the South American citizenship goal for which residence agreements are being extended".
He said that actions were being encouraged to improve "cooperation in the fight against civil uncertainty and international organized crime, to improve access to medicine and affordable Internet in all corners of South America, and to take joint and effective action against the risks of natural disasters".
When Europe is in crisis, "economic consolidation (Latin America) is not to be a winning factor, but to serve to increase our productivity and show our nations a better future", added Humala.
"We have decided to prioritise a group of 31 symbolic projects that will improve transport connectivity between different parts of South America, especially rural and border areas . . . so that our countries are better connected and create new economic ties", the Peruvian president said in a statement read.
He mentioned that five of these projects concern Peru and its coastal-to-Brazil cross-border axis and two others concern better connectivity with Ecuador, but did not give further details.
The final document also touched on the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve to bring it back to the Union of South American Nations", which it is currently excluded from.
Another issue highlighted by the summit was the need for Latin America to remain a prosperous and peaceful region that is integrated and has good neighbourly relations.
In this regard, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said before attending a regional meeting that he hoped to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, in Mexico on Saturday to respectfully discuss the International Court of Justice's ruling on the maritime border dispute, which is disputed by Bogotá.
