The Head of State of Ecuador attended today the sixth Summit of Heads of State and Government of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR), which concluded with calls for greater regional integration to maintain development, equality and security.
Victims of AIDS today are the result of late diagnosis
Fabrizi was 21 when he was confirmed HIV positive.
"It was like a flash of lightning struck me", she recalls, recalling a moment of truth that the doctor tried to "soften up a little", but apparently without success.
The boy kept it from the family.
He decided to take his illness to his own devices and began to learn about it, with such dedication that he had already celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients in the HIV Unit at the Civil Hospital of Guadalajara (HCG), where he joined in 1994 after several struggles with the disease.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, something unimaginable in the early 1990s, when there were many doubts, few treatment options and greater stigma.
Even the director of the Mexico Institute for Social Security (IMSS) clinic did not say goodbye to him "because he had a cutting wound".
Back then, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
Now it's possible to survive with this syndrome and live fully.
However, many people do not know about their illness and only come to know about it after the virus has destroyed the body and activated the immune system, and then become victims of random infections.
31 years since the world's first recorded cases of AIDS, or at least the first documented cases, "are a great achievement that the life expectancy of a patient who begins treatment in a timely and appropriate manner is exactly the same as that of healthy people", said Jaime Andrade Villanueva, head of the HIV Unit at the Civil Hospital in Guadalajara, confirming this information in a prestigious scientific publication in April this year.
Infectious diseases and HIV/AIDS specialist Andrade Villanueva explained that scientists have concluded that since 2008, AIDS is not a death sentence, but that the length of survival and full life depends on the degree of immune system impairment of the patients diagnosed with the disease, with those who do not use drugs being better off: people with 200 CD4 cells can live up to 30 years and people with 500 CD4 cells up to 50 years.
Simply put, this means that a person diagnosed with HIV at age 25 can "live without problems up to 75 years if treatment is followed", the doctor explained in an interview.
To highlight this progress, it is appropriate to recall that the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
Although death rates have declined significantly in recent years and the number of people who died of AIDS in Mexico has fallen from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (UN's Joint Programme on HIV/AIDS - UNAIDS), it is also true that, according to national statistics, 60 percent of AIDS-related deaths have occurred since the outbreak.
In 2011, 255 people died in Jalisco alone, and as of May this year, 187 people have died. However, since 2005, universal access to antiretroviral drugs has been ensured.
Why do people still die from disease?
"I don't think the problem is with access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's how it's done at our hospital.
At least in the last 12 years, we have not exhausted our medicines. The problem is that patients arrive at a very advanced stage because they do not know the status of the disease, or the late stage of the disease".
He adds: "Nine out of ten patients come when they have a related infection, and the only thing to do to increase the overall mortality rate is to diagnose the disease early, and so large-scale testing is needed for all those who request it".
He agrees with the specialists and officials of the Jalisco State AIDS Prevention Council and with patients like Fabrizio, who came to get tests done in a private lab just because a friend had done it, and despite his young age, he had AIDS and also had Kaposi's sarcoma, a tumor disease that is one of the common complications.
"Everything changes when you know you have AIDS.
Some people think they're going to die, and they don't want to know anything else.
"If I'm going to die, I'd rather get out of here three times a week", they say, but that's not my case.
I've changed for the better, eating healthy, exercising, taking medication".
To this day, all his parents know is that he had cancer.
"I'm living a normal life like everyone else.
I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I lead an active sex life, but responsibly, I take care of myself and my partner", says Fabrizio, who accepted the invitation to share his experience with the MILENIO JALISCO daily to motivate those who are afraid by his testimony on World AIDS Day.
"Let them get tested. If they're at risk, let them know as soon as possible if they're HIV positive, and if they've been diagnosed, let them know that they can live like anyone else if they're responsible".
This message summarizes the keynote address for the fight against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms at the counter
There is a huge gap between health programs and ordinary citizens, said Ricardo Salazar, a Guadalajara journalist who investigates HIV information.
And the biggest gap is in prevention.
In places that do this, "the distribution of condoms has really increased, we used to get one or two, now we get a hundred condoms in packages, which is very good, but there are still people who don't have access to condoms", he said.
Adolescents are among the most vulnerable to new infections.
"What do you want it for?" is a common question filled with irony and judgment from social workers, school counselors, pharmacy staff, and health care workers that teens want to avoid, says the reporter.
He proposed changing this inefficient distribution so that condoms are not just on the counter but in the 100s in the dosers in public toilets, in places where young people often go.
"It's not promoting promiscuity.
It's not even about "paying for a beer and a motel", as Governor Emilio González responded to a question about whether he would approve of distributing condoms in his district.
It's best to make condoms available to those who are already having sex", he said.
Key numbers in the State of Jalisco
There were 13,435 cases of AIDS (12,158 cases and 1,317 cases of HIV).
This is the fourth highest number of new and confirmed cases of AIDS in Mexico and the 13th highest number of HIV cases.
92% of the infection is sexually transmitted, 6% is blood-borne and 2% perinatal.
It is estimated that about 50,000 people may live with HIV, since there are four to five people per recorded case who are unaware of the disease.
The judgment upheld by the United States Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit, which does not recognise the restructuring of Grupo Vitro's debt due to bankruptcy in Mexico, sets an unfortunate precedent for any national enterprise with branches in a neighbouring country and a solvency problem.
The restructuring procedures, which are permitted by Mexican law, do not appear to apply in the land of the stars, despite international agreements.
The approval of the judgment handed down on June 15 of last year by Judge Harlin Hall in the North Texas Bankruptcy Court leaves the Mexican company practically defenseless against the possibility of confiscation of their property on the other side of the El Bravo River.
However, the ruling opens the door for the major Mexican glassmaker to appeal to the United States Supreme Court on three occasions.
To begin with, while the judge in this case claims that creditors are to be governed by the United States insolvency law, the New Orleans-based Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals says that the main procedure is to rule on bankruptcy in Mexico.
First, this would indicate the ignorance of international procedural cooperation in insolvency cases of multinational enterprises.
In essence, a model United Nations law for the unification of international trade law was created for this purpose, which is appointed by the American Law Institute as an arbitrator.
Second, the judgment states that without a vote by the branches of the internal structure of the undertakings, where the debt of the parent company Vitro to the branches is recognised, the required majority for the approval of the restructuring would not have been achieved.
However, Mexican law allows this possibility.
The fact is that the Vitro case was not the first to adopt this scheme.
There are half a dozen examples like Agremex and Comercial Mexicana whose in-house debt was guaranteed by the Federal Bankruptcy Court.
Furthermore, it is true that even after the votes of the branches were counted, the creditors - who had taken Vitro to court in the United States, i.e. the 'sup' funds such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited - would not have achieved a majority.
They'd get about 45 percent to 37 percent of the vote.
The Court of Appeal shall not take this information into account.
From another perspective, the court blames Vitro for the difficult situation it has faced since 2008 - against the backdrop of the severe economic crisis that hit the United States.
Meanwhile, the family firm of Gonzaloza Sady will appeal the new judgment directly to the Court of Appeal, so that the judgment will be held in full participation, that is, with the participation of five judges, since only three voted initially.
If he fails here, he will seek a review of the case by a higher court, in this case the Supreme Court of the United States.
It is important to note that the Court omitted a document sent by the Mexican Government as an amicus curiae brief detailing Vitro's conduct under the Competition Act and pointing out that the company facilitated itself by relying on agreements signed by both countries to confront the law with Chapter 15 of the United States Bankruptcy Code.
It also points out that the country has submitted to the principles of the United Nations Commission on International Trade, i.e. the rules for international insolvency cases, which guarantee equality between debtors and creditors.
A two-way collision: a penalty for Vitro and the state.
