Hector "Hetin" Reyes: "Basketball was my life"
World basketball champion Héctor "Hetin" Reyes has been involved in the hall sport for over 60 years and has traveled the world thanks to it.
Few people in Puerto Rico have as many memories of the history of local basketball as Hector "Hetin" Reyes.
Before he suffered a stroke in 2008, Reyes was involved in the sport for more than 60 years, whether as a junior player, a player in the National Basketball League (BSN), the owner and coach of the Vaqueros de Bayamón team in the National Basketball League, or the president of the Puerto Rican Basketball Federation.
"I've had many roles in basketball throughout my life, including several simultaneously, like being the president of the BSN National League in the 1990s, the general manager of the national team, and the president of the federation", Reyes recalled visiting reporters at Primera Hora's home in Bayamon, where he has lived for more than 50 years with Isabel, his loyal wife.
"Basketball was my life".
Reyes is not exaggerating.
The walls of his home, almost all decorated with photographs and memorabilia from his long career, bear witness to this.
Bayamón in the heart
The biggest move of all guards is the one that reminds him of his time at Los Vaqueros from the mid-1950s, where he was a player until 1982, when he also celebrated 15 years as a co-owner or team owner.
"It was my best years, the one I enjoyed the most, because I had the opportunity to participate in eight championships with the Los Vaqueros since 1967, whether as owner, co-owner, or coach.
