Larry Hagman, born September 21, 1931 in Forth Worth, Texas, is best known for his starring role as John Ross Ewing, better known as "J.R". in the television series Dallas, which portrayed a man who acted recklessly and was cunning and manipulative.
Larry Hagman, whose role as the predatory oil tycoon J.R. Ewing on the television series Dallas became a symbol of the 1980s famine, has died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who returned as J.R. in the new Dallas series this year, died, according to the family's official announcement, provided by Dallas production company Warner Bros. to Associated Press, on Friday afternoon from complications related to cancer.
"Larry returned to his beloved hometown of Dallas, where he reprised the iconic role he loved most", his family said.
Larry's family and his closest friends were with him in Dallas for Thanksgiving.
"Linda Gray, who was Hagman's wife in the original and new series, was with Hagman at the time of his death at Dallas Hospital", her agent Jeffrey Lane reported.
He brought joy to all he knew.
"He was creative, generous, fun, kind, kind, and talented, and I will miss him so much.
He was unique and lived his life to the fullest", Linda Gray said in a statement.
Hagman was diagnosed with cirrhosis of the liver in 1992, and he himself admitted to drinking heavily over the years.
In 1995, he was diagnosed with a malignant tumor in his liver and Hagman underwent a transplant.
Years before the Dallas series aired, Hagman was a TV celebrity as the decent guy in the light-hearted comedy I Dream of Jeannie that aired on NBC from 1965 to 1970.
Here he played Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life changes when he meets an attractive girl (a female genie) played by Barbara Eden, and takes her home to live with him.
He also starred in two short-lived sitcoms, The Good Life (NBC, 1971-72) and Here We Go Again (ABC, 1973).
His film roles included critically acclaimed roles in The Group, Harry and Tonto and Primary Colors.
But it wasn't until Hangman's masterpiece in the form of an incredibly repugnant J.R. that he reached the top of the charts.
A CBS drama series about the Ewing clan and other characters around them aired from April 1978 to May 1991.
The promotional slogan "Who shot Jajra?" which was supposed to raise expectations about the thrilling work, where Hangman's character is nearly murdered, has caused not only a huge amount of speculation from audiences around the world, but also the risk of millions of dollars in box office receipts.
That also helped this piece set a record for viewing.
The November 1980 episode, in which the answer was revealed, was watched by an average of 41 million television viewers, making Dallas the second most watched entertainment show in history after MASH ended its run in 1983, with 50 million viewers.
J.R. was shot by his sister-in-law Kristin (played by Mary Crosby).
Kristin got pregnant with J.R., and then he threatened to call her a prostitute if she didn't leave town, but there were others who had reason to attack him.
Hagman played Ewing, a greedy greedy man with a charismatic smile: a cunning businessman and an unfaithful husband who tried to get his alcoholic wife, Sue Ellen (Linda Gray), to be hospitalized.
"I know what I want J.R. to have on the gravestone", Hagman said in 1988.
It should read, "Here lies the honorable citizen J.R. Ewing".
This is the only thing he didn't do.
Victoria Principal, who starred in the original series, recalled Hagman on Friday as someone who was "great on and off the screen".
He is unforgettable and irreplaceable to millions of admirers around the world and in the hearts of all of us who have had the good fortune to know and love him.
