Starting a course exploring "the end of the world"
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes like nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
When religion professor Stuart Charmé decided to take a course on the end of the world this semester, he knew that there was an irresistible temptation: The end of the "long number" of Mayans, which is scheduled for December 21, was taken by many as evidence that the end of the world was coming.
Charme had no idea what was coming in the next few months: catastrophic Hurricane Sandy, a budget deficit that some call "debt Armageddon", and the growing conflict that is dragging Israel into, the place where, according to Christian theorists, the Apocalypse begins.
"I didn't realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester ever", Charme told Rutgers University students in Camden, New Jersey, this week.
When you think about what's happening in the world today, like we have 30 days left, it's a really good time.
And remember, bad means good for the apocalyptic thinkers.
And he's not the only professor offering end of the world courses this semester, which is theoretically the last in history.
At Temple University, assistant professor Barry Vacker is conducting a course on "Medias, Culture and the End of the World".
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes like nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
"We're looking at why these ideas spread over time", he says, "and how they offer hypothetical scenarios that govern certain human behavior".
For example, if nuclear material gets into the hands of terrorists, war could break out.
This month, students are analyzing apocalyptic movies and exploring how they differ from real-life examples.
"I tried to inform students about what is possible, likely, credible, and impossible", says Vacker.
On the main campus of Penn State University, Latin American history professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of art history and anthropology, gathered to organize a course simply titled The End of the World.
"We're not joining 2012 because we always count on the possibility of rearranging the course if the world doesn't end", Restall said.
Despite the "threat of collapse", students must study, develop projects and take final exams.
Penn State's final exam will be held on the eve of the Apocalypse, giving students no choice but to work "until the eve of the supposed end of the world", Restall said.
The courses have become quite popular.
"It expanded to two hours", Restall said of his high-residency course, which had 35 students enrolled.
Weeks and weeks before the start of the semester, we were getting emails asking if there was room left.
The students themselves say that the course is one of the most interesting.
"It's fascinating to see what people do to comfort themselves", said Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old student of religion and sociology at Rutgers University in Camden, New Jersey.
And so apocalyptic, secular, or religious thinking is just a matter of comfort or lack thereof.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old psychology and nursing student, said he'd seen all the apocalyptic movies.
"I've never heard of a class that could teach it", he said.
"I'm enjoying it".
But no student interviewed, let alone the professor, said they believed in a December 21 deadline.
"Our first project was about Mayan prediction, and in a way we're going to refute it", said Julie Zeglen, a 21-year-old senior at Temple University in West Chester.
"The Mayans never predicted the end of the world; it's just a key point in the calendar", Restall said.
But he added that there is an apocalyptic anxiety in Western culture that dates back several centuries, that people respond to changes in their environment with predictions of the end of the world.
The Internet has caused a surge of speculation.
"Otherwhere people don't think about it", he said.
That's what happens in the vast majority of the English-speaking world.
